05671nam a22008775i 9780231551076DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20202020nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2020017167  a97802315510767 a10.7312/katz194902doi  a(DE-B1597)566462  a(OCoLC)1229161559  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aQ334.7 4aQ334.7b.K38 2020 7aSOC0260002bisacsh04a303.48/342231 aKatz, Yarden, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aArtificial Whiteness :bPolitics and Ideology in Artificial Intelligence /cYarden Katz. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource :b25 b&w figures  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- tI FORMATION -- t1 In the Service of Empire -- t2 In the Service of Capital -- tII SELF AND THE SOCIAL ORDER -- t3 Epistemic Forgeries and Ghosts in the Machine -- t4 Adaptation, Not Abolition: Critical AI Experts and Carceral- Positive Logic -- t5 Artificial Whiteness -- tIII ALTERNATIVES -- t6 Dissenting Visions: From Autopoietic Love to Embodied War -- t7 A Generative Refusal -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDramatic statements about the promise and peril of artificial intelligence for humanity abound, as an industry of experts claims that AI is poised to reshape nearly every sphere of life. Who profits from the idea that the age of AI has arrived? Why do ideas of AI’s transformative potential keep reappearing in social and political discourse, and how are they linked to broader political agendas?Yarden Katz reveals the ideology embedded in the concept of artificial intelligence, contending that it both serves and mimics the logic of white supremacy. He demonstrates that understandings of AI, as a field and a technology, have shifted dramatically over time based on the needs of its funders and the professional class that formed around it. From its origins in the Cold War military-industrial complex through its present-day Silicon Valley proselytizers and eager policy analysts, AI has never been simply a technical project enabled by larger data and better computing. Drawing on intimate familiarity with the field and its practices, Katz instead asks us to see how AI reinforces models of knowledge that assume white male superiority and an imperialist worldview. Only by seeing the connection between artificial intelligence and whiteness can we prioritize alternatives to the conception of AI as an all-encompassing technological force.Bringing together theories of whiteness and race in the humanities and social sciences with a deep understanding of the history and practice of science and computing, Artificial Whiteness is an incisive, urgent critique of the uses of AI as a political tool to uphold social hierarchies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aArtificial intelligencexMoral and ethical aspects. 0aArtificial intelligencexPolitical aspects. 0aImperialism and science. 0aLogicxPolitical aspects. 0aMale domination (Social structure) 0aMale domination (Social structure). 0aWhite supremacy movementsxPhilosophy. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh  aAI.  aArtificial Intelligence.  ahistory of computing.  ahistory of technology.  awhite supremacy.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311071097708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:d